Great Learning - Capstone Project - NLP | Automated Ticket Assignment¶

  • Submitted By: Gaurav, Karishma, Lavanya, Pallavi and Swati
  • Status : Complete (EDA, Feature Engineering & Selection)
  • Date of Submission : 19-April-2020
  • Dataset : https://drive.google.com/drive/u/0/folders/1xOCdNI2R5hiodskIJbj-QySMQs6ccehL

Problem Statement¶

One of the key activities of any IT function is to ensure there is no impact to the Business operations through Incident Management process. An incident is an unplanned interruption to an IT service or reduction in the quality of an IT service that affects the Users and the Business.

The main goal of Incident Management process is to provide a quick fix / workarounds or solutions that resolves the interruption and restores the service to its full capacity to ensure no business impact.

These incidents are created by various stakeholders (Business Users, IT Users and Monitoring Tools) within IT Service Management Tool and are assigned to Service Desk teams (L1 / L2 teams).

The goal of this project is to build a classifier that can classify the incidents by analysing text.

Solution¶

The solution is to build a classification model that can analyse the text and classify to appropriate Service Desk team.

Approach¶

  • Analyse and Understand the structure of data
  • Visualize data
  • Text preprocessing
  • Create word vocabulary and Tokens
  • Build a Classification model
  • Train the model
  • Test the Model

def wordCloudText(data, title):
  title = ("Most Frequent words in ") + title
  stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
  wordcloud = WordCloud(background_color='black', stopwords=stopwords, max_words=200,
                        max_font_size=40, random_state=42).generate(str(data))
  print(wordcloud)
  fig = plt.figure(1,figsize = (20, 8))
  plt.imshow(wordcloud)
  plt.title(title ,fontsize=30)
  plt.axis('off')
  plt.show()

Text Cleaning¶

In [0]:
import string 
import re

# Function for Text Cleaning with regex. Pass the column
def text_preprocessing(df_column):
  data = df_column.values.tolist() # Convert to list
  temp = []
  for sentence in data:
      sentence = sentence.replace("select the following link to view the disclaimer in an alternate language", '')  # remove disclaimer text      
      sentence = re.sub(r"\[(.*?)\]"," ", sentence)  # remove text in []
      sentence = re.sub(r"\((.*?)\)"," ", sentence)  # remove text in ()
      sentence = re.sub(r"[[h][t][t][p][\S]+|[w][w][w][\S]+|[\S]+[@][\S]+"," ", sentence)  # remove email addresses, web address and urls
      sentence = re.sub(r"[\S]+[\d]+[\S]+"," ", sentence) # remove alphanumerics and numerics (dates, time, request id etc.)
      sentence = re.sub(r"\W(?<!['. ])"," ", sentence)  # remove all non words with negative look back except ('. spaces) 
      sentence = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-z.| ]+"," ", sentence) # remove non-alphabetic text
      sentence = re.sub(r"[\_]+"," ", sentence) # remove underscores
      sentence = re.sub(r"[\s]+"," ", sentence) # replace multiple spaces with single space
      sentence = sentence.strip('\n')
      sentence = sentence.lower()
      temp.append(sentence)
  return(temp)

Stop words Removal, Tokenization and Lemmatization¶

In [0]:
# word tokenisation & removal of stop words & gibberish word(by typos, anonymised names)

# Remove stopwords
df_v2['Summary'] = df_v2['Summary'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x.split() if word not in (stop_words)]))

# Remove words not in Englsih Dictionary (typos, anonymised names)
df_v2['Summary'] = df_v2['Summary'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in x.split() if word in (words)]))

# Tokenise 'Summary' column
data = df_v2.Summary.values.tolist()
data = [list(tokenize(sentences)) for sentences in data]

# lemmetise words
wordnet_lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
temp = []
for eachrow in data:
    lemma_words = []
    for eachword in eachrow:
        eachword = wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(eachword, pos = "n")
        eachword = wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(eachword, pos = "v")
        eachword = wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(eachword, pos = ("a"))
        lemma_words.append(eachword)
    temp.append(lemma_words)
data = temp

data = [(" ".join(sentence))  for sentence in data]

df_v2['Summary'] = data

#cleaned data
df_v3 = df_v2.copy()
# If EXCLUDE_CALLER is set to False then add Caller information to Summary (usernames/ids).
if not(EXCLUDE_CALLER):
  df_v3['Caller'] =  df['Caller']
  df_v3['Caller'] =  df_v3['Caller'].apply(lambda x: x.replace(" ", "_"))
  df_v3["Summary"] = df_v3['Summary'].str.cat(df_v3['Caller'], sep = ". ")
df_v3.drop(['Caller'], axis=1, inplace=True)
df_lstm = df_v3 # Saved for lstm model

TF-IDF WITHOUT SAMPLING¶

In this project we will use tf-idf to transforms text to feature vectors.

In [0]:
maxlen = 0
for sentence in data:
    if (maxlen < sentence.count(' ')+1 ):
        maxlen = sentence.count(' ')+1

print(maxlen)   

# Create Weighted Word Vectors
tfidf_vectors = TfidfVectorizer(min_df=3,max_features= maxlen)
tfidf_db = tfidf_vectors.fit_transform(data).toarray()

Model Building¶

For this dataset, we will build some traditional models and RNN.

  • Multnomial Naive Bayes
  • Support Vector Machine
  • Decision Tree
  • Random Forest
  • Ensemble
  • LSTM
  • DNN
  • RCNN

Ensemble Techniques¶

Voting Classifier with Bagging¶

In [0]:
rf = RandomForestClassifier()
et = ExtraTreesClassifier()
knn = KNeighborsClassifier() 
svc = SVC()
rg = RidgeClassifier()
In [0]:
# Ensemble of Bagging Classifiers
clf = [rf, et, knn, svc, rg]
eclf = VotingClassifier(estimators=[('Random Forests', rf), ('Extra Trees', et), ('KNeighbors', knn), ('SVC', svc), 
                                    ('Ridge Classifier', rg)], voting='hard')
for clf, label in zip([rf, et, knn, svc, rg, eclf], ['Random Forest', 'Extra Trees', 'KNeighbors', 'SVC', 
                                                     'Ridge Classifier', 'Ensemble']):
    scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train1, y_train1, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')
    test_accuracy = round(scores.mean(),2)
    print("Accuracy: %0.2f (+/- %0.2f) [%s]" % (test_accuracy, scores.std(), label))

# Update model results in result dataframe
loc = result_df[result_df['Model']=='Bagging_Ensemble'].index
result_df['Test_Accuracy'][loc] = test_accuracy

Accuracy: 0.60 (+/- 0.01) [Random Forest]
Accuracy: 0.60 (+/- 0.01) [Extra Trees]
Accuracy: 0.58 (+/- 0.01) [KNeighbors]
Accuracy: 0.60 (+/- 0.01) [SVC]
Accuracy: 0.59 (+/- 0.01) [Ridge Classifier]
Accuracy: 0.61 (+/- 0.01) [Ensemble]

Observations:

  1. The Training accuracy is 67.48% and testing accuracy is 59.16% with Naive Bayes Model. The model can predict True Positives and False Negatives equally.
  2. The Training accuracy is around 80.81% and testing accuracy is around 59.90% with SVC. The model can predict True Positives and False Negatives equally.
  3. The training accuracy is around 88.47% and testing accuracy is around 51.91% with Decision Trees. The model can predict True Positives and False Negatives almost equally.
  4. The training accuracy is around 88.45% and testing accuracy is around 58.65% with Random Forests. The model can predict True Positives and False Negatives almost equally.
  5. Ensemble of Bagging Classifiers gives 61% accuracy with hard voting.
  6. Ensemble of Boosting Classifiers gives 58% accuracy with hard voting.

Model Tuning¶

We will fine tune all the models built to see if we can improve the performance

Multinomial Naive Bayes¶

In [0]:
def find_optimal_k(X,y, lr_list):  
  # empty list that will hold cv scores
  scores = []
  for lr in lr_list:
    model_nb = MultinomialNB(alpha = lr)
    model = model_nb.fit(X_train1, y_train1)
    # predict the response on the crossvalidation train
    predict = model.predict(X_test1)
    
    # evaluate accuracy
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test1, predict, normalize=True)
    scores.append(accuracy)
    
    # changing to misclassification error
    mean_square_error = [1 - x for x in scores]

  # determining best alpha
  optimal_alpha = lr_list[mean_square_error.index(min(mean_square_error))]
  print('\nThe optimal alpha is ', optimal_alpha)

  plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
  plt.plot(lr_list, mean_square_error,color='blue', linestyle='dashed', marker='o', markerfacecolor='red', markersize=10)
  plt.title('Error Rate vs. alpha Value')
  plt.xlabel('alpha')
  plt.ylabel('Error Rate')

  print("the misclassification error for each k value is : ", np.round(mean_square_error,3))
    
  return optimal_alpha
In [0]:
lr_lst = np.arange(0.00001, 0.001, 0.00001)
best_lr = find_optimal_k(X_train1 ,y_train1, lr_lst)
print("The optimal K found is: ", best_lr)

Shuffleshit to find least fit time, and average train and test score

In [0]:
NB_Algorithm = MultinomialNB(alpha = best_lr)

cv_split = ShuffleSplit(n_splits = 10, test_size = .4, train_size = .6, random_state = 42)
cv_results = cross_validate(NB_Algorithm, X1,y1, cv  = cv_split, return_train_score=True)

print('The least fit time is:', cv_results['fit_time'].mean(), "\nThe training score average is:", 100*cv_results['train_score'].mean(), "\nThe test score average is:",  100*cv_results['test_score'].mean())

The least fit time is: 0.03308622837066651 
The training score average is: 67.71683168316832 
The test score average is: 59.10602910602911

By trying different learning rates, the best value is achieved at 0.00098, which gives a test accuracy of 59.10% and training accuracy of 67.71%. By using ShuffleSplit with 10 splits(creating random samples of the entire dataset during each iteration to generate a training set and a test set) we get an Average Train Accuracy of 67.71% and Average Test Accuracy of 59.10% with the least fit-time for fitting the estimator on the train set for each cv split, of 0.033 seconds.

Support Vector Machine¶

The kernel used for SVM in this project is 'linear'. We can use grid search to get optimal parameters that gives best accuracy

In [0]:
#Set parameters for grid search
param = {
 'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100] , 'gamma': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],'kernel': ['linear'],
 'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100] , 'gamma': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],'kernel': ['rbf'],
 'C':[0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100] , 'kernel':['poly']
                   }             

model_svm = GridSearchCV(SVC(random_state=0), param, cv=10, scoring='accuracy')

In [0]:
print('Building model...')
LSTM_Model2 = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
              tf.keras.layers.Embedding(vocab_size, output_dim=100, input_length=maxlen),
              tf.keras.layers.LSTM(64, return_sequences=True,dropout=0.2),
              tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
              tf.keras.layers.TimeDistributed(Dense(32, activation='relu')),
              tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
              tf.keras.layers.Dense(74, activation='softmax')])

LSTM_Model2.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='adam',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

print('Training the model...')
# checkpoint for validation accuracy
#LSTM_Model2.load_weights("LSTM_Model2_Weights.best.hdf5")
filepath="LSTM_Model2_Weights.best.hdf5"
checkpoint = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(filepath, monitor='val_accuracy', verbose=1, save_best_only=True,mode='max')
callbacks_list = [checkpoint]
# Fit the model
LSTM_Model2.fit(X_train_p, y_train_p, validation_split=0.2, epochs=100, batch_size=100,  shuffle=True, callbacks=callbacks_list, verbose=1)
# Save Model and Weights locally
LSTM_Model2.save("LSTM_Model2.h5")
print("LSTM_Model2 and weights to disk")
print('Model Trained')
print('evaluating the model...')

In [0]:
def multiclass_roc_auc_score(y_test, yhat_classes, average="weighted"):
    lb = LabelBinarizer()
    lb.fit(y_test)
    y_test = lb.transform(y_test)
    yhat_classes = lb.transform(yhat_classes)
    return roc_auc_score(y_test, yhat_classes, average="weighted")

# recall: tp / (tp + fn)
recall = recall_score(y_test_p, yhat_classes, average='weighted')
print('Recall: %f' % recall)
# f1: 2 tp / (2 tp + fp + fn)
f1 = f1_score(y_test_p, yhat_classes, average='weighted')
print('F1 score: %f' % f1)

# Build a DNN Model for Text classification

def Model_DNN(shape, nClasses, dropout=0.5):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes
    nLayers = 4 # number of  hidden layer

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    for i in range(0,nLayers):
        model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=node,activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

                              verbose=2)

Analyzing various architectures of DNN¶

# DNN2 - Analyzing the DNN with input same as DNN1 and hidden with double the nodes of that of the input and 4 layers.
def Model_DNN2(shape, nClasses, dropout=0.5):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes
    nLayers = 4 # hidden layers

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    for i in range(0,nLayers):
        model.add(Dense(units = 2*node,activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

model_DNN2 = Model_DNN2(X_train.shape[1], 74 )

model_DNN2.fit(X_train, y_train,
                              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
                              epochs=20,
                              batch_size=100,
                              verbose=2)

# Final evaluation of the model
scores_DNN_train = model_DNN2.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
scores_DNN_test = model_DNN2.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
y_pred = model_DNN2.predict(X_test)
print("Train Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_train[1]*100))
print("Test Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_test[1]*100))

# DNN3 - Analyzing the DNN1 with 8 layers

def Model_DNN3(shape, nClasses, dropout=0.5):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes
    nLayers = 8 # number of  hidden layer

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    for i in range(0,nLayers):
        model.add(Dense(units = node,activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

model_DNN3 = Model_DNN3(X_train.shape[1], 74 )

#fit the model
model_DNN3.fit(X_train, y_train,
                              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
                              epochs=20,
                              batch_size=100,
                              verbose=2)

#evaluate the model
scores_DNN_train = model_DNN3.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
scores_DNN_test = model_DNN3.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
print("Train Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_train[1]*100))
print("Test Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_test[1]*100))

# DNN4 - Analyzing the DNN with input same as DNN1 and hidden with double the nodes of that of the input and 8 layers.

def Model_DNN4(shape, nClasses, dropout=0.5):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes
    nLayers = 8 # number of  hidden layer

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    for i in range(0,nLayers):
        model.add(Dense(units = 2*node,activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

model_DNN4 = Model_DNN4(X_train.shape[1], 74 )

                              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),

# DNN5 - change dropout hyper-paramter
# seems like the Deeper the networks, the accuracy gets worse. Settling on DNN with 4 hidden layers and tuning the other parameters.

def Model_DNN5(shape, nClasses, dropout=0.2):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes
    nLayers = 4 # number of  hidden layer

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    for i in range(0,nLayers):
        model.add(Dense(units = node ,activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

model_DNN5 = Model_DNN5(X_train.shape[1], 74 )

#fit the model
model_DNN5.fit(X_train, y_train,
                              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
                              epochs=20,
                              batch_size=100,
                              verbose=2)

#evaluate the model
scores_DNN_train = model_DNN5.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
scores_DNN_test = model_DNN5.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
print("Train Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_train[1]*100))
print("Test Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_test[1]*100))

# NN7 - Simple NN - 1 input, 1 output and 1 hidden layer and no dropout.

def Model_NN(shape, nClasses):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(units = node,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

Model_NN = Model_NN(X_train.shape[1], 74 )

#fit the model
Model_NN.fit(X_train, y_train,
                              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
                              epochs=20,
                              batch_size=100,
                              verbose=2)

#evaluate the model
scores_DNN_train = Model_NN.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
scores_DNN_test = Model_NN.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
print("Train Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_train[1]*100))
print("Test Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_test[1]*100))

# DNN8 - Activation funciton is sigmoid instead of relu

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='sigmoid'))

# DNN9 - change dropout hyper-paramter
# seems like the Deeper the networks, the accuracy gets worse. Settling on DNN with 4 hidden layers and tuning the other parameters.
# Reducing the hidden nodes by half the input no

def Model_DNN9(shape, nClasses, dropout=0.2):
    model = Sequential()
    node = maxlen #512 # number of nodes
    nLayers = 4 # number of  hidden layer

    model.add(Dense(node,input_dim=shape,activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    for i in range(0,nLayers):
        model.add(Dense(units = node/2,activation='relu'))
        model.add(Dropout(dropout))
    model.add(Dense(nClasses, activation='softmax'))
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='adam',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()  
    return model

Model_DNN9 = Model_DNN5(X_train.shape[1], 74 )

#fit the model
Model_DNN9.fit(X_train, y_train,
                              validation_data=(X_test,y_test),
                              epochs=20,
                              batch_size=100,
                              verbose=2)

#evaluate the model
scores_DNN_train = Model_DNN9.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
scores_DNN_test = Model_DNN9.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
print("Train Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_train[1]*100))
print("Test Acc: %.2f%",  (scores_DNN_test[1]*100))

RCNN¶

In [0]:
def RCNN_model():
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Embedding(vocab_size, output_dim=100, input_length=maxlen))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    model.add(Conv1D(filters=250,
                 kernel_size=3,
                 padding='valid',
                 activation='relu',
                 strides=1))
    model.add(MaxPooling1D())
    model.add(LSTM(128))
    model.add(Dense(74))
    model.add(Activation('softmax'))

    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              optimizer='adam',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
    model.summary()
   
    return model

RCNN_model = RCNN_model()

print('Train...')
RCNN_model.fit(X_train_p, y_train_p,
          batch_size=300,
          epochs=20,
          validation_data=(X_test_p, y_test_p))
score_train, acc_train = RCNN_model.evaluate(X_train_p, y_train_p,
                            batch_size=300)
score, acc = RCNN_model.evaluate(X_test_p, y_test_p,
                            batch_size=300)

print('Test...')
